06878nam a22011175i 9780813579337DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135793377 a10.36019/97808135793372doi  a(DE-B1597)526062  a(OCoLC)956481134  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aRC386.2 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a616.8047122300aCerebral Herniation Syndromes and Intracranial Hypertension /ced. by Matthew Koenig. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aUpdates in Neurocritical Care00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tCONTRIBUTING AUTHORS -- t1. The Pathophysiology of Intracranial Hypertension and Cerebral Herniation Syndromes -- t2. Intracranial Pressure Monitoring and Waveforms -- t3. Controversies in Intracranial Pressure Monitoring -- t4. Cerebral Herniation Syndromes -- t5. Osmotic Agents for the Treatment of Intracranial Hypertension and Cerebral Edema -- t6. Metabolic Suppression and Induced Hypothermia for the Treatment of Intracranial Hypertension -- t7. The Surgical Management of Intracranial Hypertension and Cerebral Herniation Syndromes -- t8. The Multicompartment Management of Intracranial Hypertension -- t9. The Role of Intracranial Pressure in Multimodality Monitoring Strategies -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen the brain suffers an injury, the effects can be delayed and unpredictable. Cerebrospinal fluid can slowly build up, causing dangerously high levels of intracranial pressure (ICP), and the brain tissue can be displaced into adjacent compartments, resulting in cerebral herniation syndrome (CHS). Within the burgeoning field of neurocritical care, experts are just beginning to understand the nuanced, sometimes counterintuitive relationship between ICP and CHS. Written by leading researchers who also have extensive first-hand clinical experience treating brain injury patients, Cerebral Herniation Syndromes and Intracranial Hypertension provides an up-to-date guide to this complex aspect of neurocritical care. Drawing from expertise gained working in high-volume medical centers, the book’s contributors reveal that there is no universal metric for gauging acceptable levels of intracranial pressure. Instead, they demonstrate the best practices for offering patients individualized care, based on their specific conditions and manifest symptoms. Bringing together internationally-renowned neurocritical care experts from a variety of neurology, critical care, surgery, and neurosurgery disciplines, this volume takes a comprehensive look at a complicated issue. A concise, practical, and timely review, Cerebral Herniation Syndromes and Intracranial Hypertension offers vital information for all medical personnel concerned with improving neurocritical patient care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBrain damage. 0aBrainxDiseases. 0aEncephalocelexTreatment. 0aEncephalocele. 0aIntracranial hypertension. 0aNeurophysiologic monitoring. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh1 aBajgur, Suhas S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBajgur, Suhas.1 aChang, Tiffany R.1 aChang, Tiffany R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, H. Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, H. Alex.1 aDeJesus-Alvelo, Indira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeJesus-Alvelo, Indira.1 aDurrant, Julia C.1 aDurrant, Julia C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinson, Holly E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela